            "answer_text": "Original question : Do Southern Italians have some Albanian ancestry? Answer : this answer is not wrong and not right.. It is just formuleded bad. Why? Do SOME Southern Italians have some Albanian ancestry? YES. Do (all) Southern Italians have some Albanian ancestry? NO. Often, during the centuries when the Turks of the Ottoman Empire invaded the Balkan Peninsula, many foreigners found a safe country in southern Italy\u2019s regions. These peoples were mainly Greeks, who have a very long history of encounters with southern Italy because in classical times to escape famine they came here and mixing with the local populations gave life to the cities of Magna Graecia, and Albanians. Magna Graecia :  The Greek populations, thanks to previous contacts with local populations or a greater strength of adaptation, have mixed completely with the population of southern Italy. In fact, in any genetic test you will see that Italians and Greeks are very close together, especially Southern Italians and Greeks. There are Griko, a minorance from south Italy that still talk in Greek, but you can see by thier dress that they are pretty near and mixed with Italian tarantella\u2019s dresses (obviously italians have many traditional dress for different traditional dances ). Grikos :  Italians without foreign ancestry with tarantella traditional dress: Calabria  Sicily  Campania :  While Albanians preserved way better their traditions and uniqueness but this was possible only because they integrated themselves less successfully. So, some Southern italians are in touch with their Albanians roots, those people call themselves Arb\u00ebresh\u00eb and their language and traditions are protected by the Italian State itself as historical minorities to be preserved. Arb\u00ebresh\u00eb speak Italian and Albanian and follow Albanian festivals, preserve traditional Albanian customs, eat recipes that are a mix between Italian and Albanian ones. This is beautiful because it is a clear manifestation of a historical period of Italy but most importantly of Albania, but it also shows that the Albanians have mixed way less than Greeks and that therefore only a few Southern Italians have some Albanian ancestors. While a lot of southern italians have some form of Greek ancestry. Plus, another difference is that Greeks settled themselves in small cities on the coast but since they mixed themselves with native Italians they spread all over the south while Arb\u00ebresh\u00eb are inside some specifical villages : Piana degli Albanesi in Sicily, Civita, Calabria in Calabria, Casalvecchio di Puglia in Apulia, Barile in Basilicata, Greci, Campania in Campania (my region), Ururi in Molise, Villa Badessa in Abruzzo. Arb\u00ebresh\u00eb in South Italy :   ",
